====================================================================================================================
TOPIC 6 — LOOPS (FOR / WHILE) — COMPLETE DETAILED NOTES (BASICS TO ADVANCED)
====================================================================================================================

A LOOP IS A CONTROL STRUCTURE THAT ALLOWS A BLOCK OF CODE TO EXECUTE REPEATEDLY UNTIL A SPECIFIED CONDITION IS MET.
LOOPS ARE USED TO AUTOMATE REPETITIVE TASKS AND ARE THE BACKBONE OF PROGRAMMING, ALGORITHMS, AND DATA STRUCTURES.

WHY LOOPS ARE IMPORTANT:
- AVOID WRITING REPEATED CODE
- PROCESS LARGE AMOUNTS OF DATA
- IMPLEMENT LOGIC FOR COUNTING, SEARCHING, PATTERNS, AND SIMULATIONS
- ESSENTIAL FOR DSA AND REAL-WORLD APPLICATIONS

TYPES OF LOOPS IN PYTHON:
1. FOR LOOP    → USED WHEN NUMBER OF ITERATIONS IS KNOWN
2. WHILE LOOP  → USED WHEN ITERATIONS DEPEND ON A CONDITION

FOR LOOP FUNDAMENTALS:
- ITERATES OVER A SEQUENCE (RANGE, STRING, LIST, ETC.)
- RANGE() FUNCTION GENERATES A SEQUENCE OF NUMBERS
- RANGE(START, STOP, STEP)
- STOP VALUE IS EXCLUSIVE
- STEP CAN BE POSITIVE OR NEGATIVE

WHILE LOOP FUNDAMENTALS:
- EXECUTES AS LONG AS CONDITION IS TRUE
- REQUIRES MANUAL INITIALIZATION AND UPDATE
- MUST ENSURE CONDITION EVENTUALLY BECOMES FALSE TO AVOID INFINITE LOOP

INFINITE LOOP:
- OCCURS WHEN LOOP CONDITION NEVER BECOMES FALSE
- COMMON CAUSES: MISSING UPDATE, WRONG CONDITION

BREAK STATEMENT:
- TERMINATES THE LOOP IMMEDIATELY
- USED WHEN CONDITION IS MET EARLIER THAN EXPECTED

CONTINUE STATEMENT:
- SKIPS CURRENT ITERATION
- JUMPS TO NEXT LOOP CYCLE

PASS STATEMENT:
- DOES NOTHING
- USED AS A PLACEHOLDER

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 0 — ABSOLUTE BASICS (LOOP INTRODUCTION)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL BUILDS COMFORT WITH LOOP SYNTAX AND SIMPLE ITERATION.

KEY IDEAS:
- PRINTING SEQUENCES
- FORWARD AND BACKWARD COUNTING
- EVEN AND ODD NUMBERS
- MULTIPLICATION TABLES
- ITERATING OVER STRINGS
- USING RANGE() WITH DIFFERENT STEPS

SKILLS DEVELOPED:
- LOOP FLOW UNDERSTANDING
- BASIC PROBLEM SOLVING
- CONFIDENCE WITH FOR AND WHILE

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 1 — VERY BASIC (COUNTING & ACCUMULATION)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL INTRODUCES ACCUMULATION USING VARIABLES.

IMPORTANT CONCEPTS:
- SUMMATION
- PRODUCT
- DIGIT EXTRACTION USING MODULUS AND DIVISION
- REVERSING NUMBERS
- PALINDROME CHECKING
- STRING CHARACTER ANALYSIS

ACCUMULATOR VARIABLE:
- A VARIABLE USED TO STORE RUNNING TOTAL
- MUST BE INITIALIZED BEFORE LOOP

COMMON PATTERNS:
- COUNTING DIGITS
- ADDING DIGITS
- TRACKING MAXIMUM AND MINIMUM VALUES

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 2 — BASIC (DECISION + LOOPS)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL COMBINES CONDITIONAL STATEMENTS WITH LOOPS.

KEY CONCEPTS:
- PRIME NUMBER LOGIC
- DIVISOR COUNTING
- ARMSTRONG, PERFECT, STRONG NUMBERS
- GCD AND LCM USING LOOPS

IMPORTANT THINKING:
- NESTED CONDITIONS INSIDE LOOPS
- EFFICIENT CHECKING
- EARLY TERMINATION USING BREAK

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 3 — BASIC+ (SERIES & NUMBER PATTERNS)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL BUILDS MATHEMATICAL THINKING USING LOOPS.

KEY SERIES:
- FIBONACCI
- ARITHMETIC PROGRESSION
- GEOMETRIC PROGRESSION
- FACTORIAL SERIES
- ALTERNATING SERIES

PATTERN LOGIC:
- IDENTIFY FORMULA
- UPDATE VARIABLES STEP BY STEP
- USE MULTIPLE VARIABLES WHEN REQUIRED

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 4 — MEDIUM (NESTED LOOPS & PATTERNS)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL INTRODUCES NESTED LOOPS.

NESTED LOOP CONCEPT:
- OUTER LOOP CONTROLS ROWS
- INNER LOOP CONTROLS COLUMNS

PATTERN THINKING:
- ROW-WISE LOGIC
- COLUMN-WISE LOGIC
- CONDITION-BASED PRINTING FOR HOLLOW PATTERNS

KEY SKILL:
- VISUALIZE OUTPUT BEFORE WRITING LOGIC

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 5 — MEDIUM+ (INPUT CONTROL & SENTINEL LOOPS)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL TEACHES REAL-WORLD LOOP CONTROL.

SENTINEL LOOP:
- LOOP CONTINUES UNTIL SPECIAL VALUE IS ENTERED
- USED WHEN NUMBER OF INPUTS IS UNKNOWN

MENU-DRIVEN PROGRAMS:
- USE WHILE TRUE
- DISPLAY MENU
- TAKE USER CHOICE
- EXECUTE ACTION
- EXIT USING BREAK

ERROR HANDLING LOGIC:
- RETRY INPUT
- LIMIT ATTEMPTS
- VALIDATION USING CONDITIONS

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 6 — HARD (ALGORITHMIC LOOP THINKING)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL INTRODUCES DSA-STYLE PROBLEMS.

KEY CONCEPTS:
- ARRAY TRAVERSAL
- TWO POINTER TECHNIQUE
- SLIDING WINDOW
- FREQUENCY COUNTING
- BASIC SORTING ALGORITHMS

THINKING APPROACH:
- REDUCE TIME COMPLEXITY
- MINIMIZE NESTED LOOPS
- USE TEMP VARIABLES EFFECTIVELY

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEVEL 7 — VERY HARD (SIMULATION & GAME LOGIC)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THIS LEVEL SIMULATES REAL SYSTEMS.

KEY IDEAS:
- STATE MANAGEMENT
- TURN-BASED LOGIC
